Hi!

There plenty of articles online that discuss how to set up a profiler for your favorite language, but not many that describe how you as an engineer can use a profiler for anything other than answering why something is slow. Here, I'll try to address how you as engineer can embed profiler into your daily workflows. I'll argue that you as a software engineer always need to have a profiler on the tip on your hands, and every production deployments should have an ability to run a get a profile.

[.text-center]
image:/img/flames/this_is_fine.jpg[]
[.text-center]
[quote]
____
This is fine.
____

NOTE: This article is illustrated with examples of flame graphs. Being able to read flame graph isn't necessary for this article, but if you find it interesting, you can read more about the flame graphs link:http://www.brendangregg.com/flamegraphs.html[here].

=== Five Flavours of Flame

There are many various scenarios in which you might want to use a profiler. Here are a few.

==== Quick wins

Sometimes it's not even necessary to perform any type of performance analysis, and even just looking at the graph might yield quick wins. As an engineer who is responsible for a service, you already have a mental model of your code. And some cases it might clash with the runtime model you're observing on the graph. These discoveries can lead to quick optimisations. This works best when you have the full context of the running app, but in some cases, even if you don't have the context, you might spot something suspicious like this.

image:/img/flames/intern_cache.png[Intern cache]

In the above case, the win was indeed very quick, it only needed to flip an option in the link:https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-core/issues/332[jackson config].

==== Removing the bottlenecks.

What do we do before releasing a new big feature? Perhaps some form of load testing to find the saturation point. While looking at the graphs, you can find a number. However, the number by itself is often useless if it's received in an artificial environment. And to make use of that number, you need to have the answer to what defines this number. So, here come the flame graphs which can explain why. Very often, the explanation allows for improving that number significantly by removing the bottlenecks like in these cases. And quite often the bottlenecks are not

Here are just a couple of examples where profiling lead to significant performance improvements in the source code.

- link:https://github.com/eclipse/jetty.project/pull/4564[Large allocations for small messages]
image:/img/flames/jetty_bytes.png[Jetty bytes]

- link:https://github.com/eclipse/jetty.project/issues/4650[Creating a websocket scans the classpath]
image:/img/flames/jetty_classpath.png[Intern cache]

==== Investigating a change

In software engineering change is the only constant. Not every change can go as smoothly as planned. It's usually easy to track down the issue when you release a new version of the application that you're building, git bisection can give you an answer in a _logN_ time. However, when you upgrade 3rd software, the answer is not to revert a particular commit but rather to figure out what's exhibiting the behaviour that shouldn't be present.

After another JDK upgrade, a team noticed that one of the services started requiring more instances to run. Comparing the flame graphs showed that the service started spending crazy 70% of the CPU time doing GC.

image:/img/flames/high_gc_before.png[Before]

A good profiler can show the GC activity down to a single method which can be incredibly convenient while for searching git history while trying to figure out what could change in the related code in the new JDK release. After figuring out the change

Figure out the related change, and tune the GC options accordingly, and the CPU usage went back to normal.

image:/img/flames/high_gc_after.png[After]

Taking this to the limits, you could generate link:http://www.brendangregg.com/blog/2014-11-09/differential-flame-graphs.html[differential flame graphs] to track all possible regressions.

==== Responding to an incident

Many of us are on-call for the services that we are working on. You build it, you run it. It's one of the most typical scenarios where having a profiler ready to go on a production system can save the day. The typical indicators signalling that you're in this situation include: it's the middle of the night, your pager is going off, the name of the alert contains CPU and the number is close to 100%. Ideally, there is already a link to a profile inside the alert. Or, at least there is a single command that'll immediately produce you a ready-to-look-at profile.

image:/img/flames/okhttp.png[]

The flame graph might not always tell you what exactly is wrong, but it will tell you why the CPU hitting 100%. Having this knowledge is critical to respond to an incident is fast as possible especially in the world where engineers are responsible for running the services they build.

==== Building a runtime mental model

As an engineer, how do you approach a new feature? Everything is a tradeoff, and applying engineering rigor generously doesn't always lead to an optimal result. Is it worth spending a day for an optimisation that shaves off 100 ms of loading an admin page that's used once a month to grab some metrics? Probably not. Is it worth spending a day to make the home page that every user of your product opens many times a day? I'd say yes.

However, not always this distinction is very clear. A method that can be in your mental model shouldn't be taking a lot of resources might do so. By "moving fast and breaking things" while introducing a change to that method, you might fail the canary deployments, introduce user errors eventually spending much more time than you would had you known the runtime model of your code.

Building a runtime mental model of your service by combining the metrics and the data from a profiler can guide your decisions on how much rigor you need to apply to a change while you're working on your software.

=== Conclusion

So, if profilers are so powerful not only for SRE or performance engineers but also for software engineers who're working on new functionality, why doesn't everyone use them as a part of their day-to-day job? I believe this is due to the high entry bar. There is very little use of getting flame graphs from you local laptop since it doesn't represent the load profile of your production environment. It's not impossible, but at a certain scale it becomes very expensive. However, profiling a running production system always requires not only expertise in setting up the tooling but also in some cases elevated permissions which works as a definite roadblock.

So, what could you do in your organisation to empower everyone use the profiler? First of all, make it accessible - getting a flame graph from a running service should be easy, safe, and secure. If I get paged for a high CPU usage, I should be able to get a flame graph using a single command, or even better the alert should already contain the graph inside.

Make it easy, and uses will come.

